    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-07-16T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-07-16T14:00:00-05:00" n="424"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d424">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">832.00 Revolutions/260: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-07-16T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 16, 1932—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>49. Your 62, July 14, 2 p.m. If Santos is in the control of insurgents the
                    Brazilian Government would have no right to close this port by decree as
                    reported in your telegram of July 12, 9 a.m., unless this decree is enforced by
                    an effective blockade. As it appears from <pb facs="0505" n="401"
                        xml:id="pg_401"/> your telegram 65, of July 15, that the Brazilian
                    authorities have given clearance to the <hi rend="italic">Angeles</hi> and the
                        <hi rend="italic">Delsud</hi>, no occasion is presented for determining the
                    legal effect of the foregoing decree. If, however, on a future occasion the
                    Brazilian Government should attempt in pursuance of this decree to interfere
                    with an American ship attempting to enter or leave Santos, you should endeavor
                    immediately to ascertain whether an effective blockade is maintained in order to
                    determine whether an occasion for protest may have arisen.</p>
                <p>The Department considers it inexpedient for you to obtain any formal opinion from
                    the Foreign Office on this subject as indicated in paragraph 2 of your telegram
                    No. 62.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
